article.headline: Devils dominate at N.C. State
article.linkText: Beard becomes Duke's all-time scorer in win
article.story:
RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Four-time Atlantic Coast Conference
champion Duke appeared primed for another tournament run, closing
out the regular season with a 90-57 victory Monday night over North
Carolina State.

"We really met a red-hot team tonight," State coach Kay Yow
said. "We knew how hot they were by the way they beat Clemson in
the game prior to us. We were really impressed by what they did in
that game."

Duke (24-3, 15-1) beat Clemson 102-45 Friday night, handing the
Tigers the worst defeat in program history. Their margin of victory
against State was the largest in their 61-game series.

"We had a really good game against Clemson, and I was anxious
to see how well we'd do on the road against another good ACC
team," Duke coach Gail Goestenkors said. "N.C. State is a tough
place to play, and they're playing well right now, so I'm really
pleased with our play."

Duke was 18 for 35 (51.4 percent) from the field in the first
half and 17-for-28 (60.7) in the second.

Reserve Brittany Hunter had 20 points and 10 rebounds, and Alana
Beard scored 22 points.

Hunter notched her second double-double as the Blue Devils
picked up their seventh straight win against the Wolfpack (16-13,
8-8 ACC).

Beard set the tempo on her first shot, a 17-footer that made her
the leading scorer among Duke players. She has 2,577 points in 129
games, moving her past Johnny Dawkins, who had 2,556.

Beard remains second on the ACC women's scoring list behind the
3,113 of Clemson's Barbara Kennedy.

"When I think about all the players she's passed, especially on
the men's side, I think it's incredible," Goestenkors said. "And
she did it within a team concept. She is one of the most unselfish
players I have ever seen."

Mistie Bass added 13 points for Duke. Kaayla Chones, playing in
her last home game for State, scored 15 points, and Kendra Bell
added 11.

Duke led 41-24 at the half, paced by 14 points from Hunter and
10 from Beard. Hunter led Duke to a 37-29 edge in rebounds.

The game was delayed for 20 minutes midway through the second
half when a shot clock malfunctioned. A replacement clock also
stopped working, and State played the last 12:37 without a timer at
its offensive end.

Hunter scored 14 points after entering the game with 10:36
remaining in the first half. She scored eight straight points in a
span of 1:47 late in the half. That sparked a 10-2 Duke run heading
into the break.

Beard scored six points in a 10-0 streak that boosted the margin
to 68-36 in the second half. Bass scored six straight points as the
Blue Devils took their biggest lead at 75-39 with 7:43 to play.
